1) How do you access a class from one package in another package?
-->You can access a class from another package in three ways:

    ✅ 1. Using import statement
    import com.app.Test;
    
    public class Main {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            Test t = new Test();
        }
    }
    ✅ 2. Using fully qualified name
    public class Main {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            com.app.Test t = new com.app.Test();
        }
    }
    ✅ 3. Using wildcard import
    import com.app.*;
    Test t = new Test();
    👉 Important condition:
    The class must be public, otherwise it cannot be accessed outside its package.


    
2) Difference between using import package.* and import package.ClassName.
-->
| Feature     | `import package.*`                                 | `import package.ClassName` |
| ----------- | -------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------- |
| Import type | Imports all classes                                | Imports only one class     |
| Performance | No major difference (Java loads only used classes) | Same                       |
| Readability | Less clear (which class is used?)                  | More clear                 |
| Recommended | Less preferred in large projects                   | Preferred                  |

👉 Example:

import java.util.*;           // all classes
import java.util.ArrayList;  // specific class



3) Can private classes be accessed from another package?
-->❌ No, private classes cannot be accessed from another package.
    
    👉 Key points:  
    In Java, top-level classes cannot be private
    Only inner classes can be private
    Private members/classes are accessible only within the same class
    
    👉 Example:
  
    class Outer {
        private class Inner {
            // cannot be accessed outside Outer
        }
    }
    
    👉 Even from another package → ❌ Not accessible
